ormans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":12,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":43,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Baliol was born in 1247, in Roxburghshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Henry de Baliol of Cavers Chamberlain of Scotland, was 56 and his mother, Lora de Valognes, was 37. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1309, in Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1247?–1309":"1247–1309","1237–1289":"1237–1289","1240–1309":"1240–1309","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1246–1265":"1246–1265","1247–1309":"1247–1309","1250–1308":"1250–1308","1251–1313":"1251–1313","1220–1309":"1220–1309","1191–1246":"1191–1246","1210–1266":"1210–1266","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1251":"1251","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1191":"1191","1247?":"1247","1